{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2001 |Team=South Carolina Gamecocks |Image=South Carolina Gamecocks wordmark.svg |ImageSize=150 |Conference=Southeastern Conference |Division=Eastern |ShortConference=SEC |CoachRank=13 |APRank=13 |BCSRank= |Record=9-3 |ConfRecord=5-3 |HeadCoach=[[Lou Holtz]] |OffCoach= |DefCoach= |OScheme= |DScheme= |Stadium=[[Williams-Brice Stadium]] (c. 80,250, grass) |Champion=Outback Bowl Champions |BowlTourney=[[2002 Outback Bowl|Outback Bowl]] vs. [[2001 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] |BowlTourneyResult=W 31â28 }} {{2001 SEC football standings}} The '''2001 [[South Carolina Gamecocks]] football team''' represented the [[University of South Carolina]] in the [[Southeastern Conference]]. The Gamecocks were led by [[Lou Holtz]] in his third season as USC head coach, and played their home games in [[Williams-Brice Stadium]] in Columbia, SC.
Carolina followed up one of the biggest turnarounds in college football history in 2000 with another successful season in 2001. The season was also notable in that the USCâMississippi State game on September 20 was the first Division I-A game played following the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|September 11]] terrorist attacks.<ref>[http://media.www.dailytexanonline.com/media/storage/paper410/news/2001/09/21/Sports/South.Carolina.Edges.Mississippi.State.1614-503874.shtml South Carolina edges Mississippi State, 16-14]</ref> On January 1, 2002, the Gamecocks defeated [[2001 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] in the [[2002 Outback Bowl]] in Tampa, Florida, and finished the season ranked #13 in both the AP and Coaches' Polls.
== Schedule==
The November 10 game played host to ESPN's [[College Gameday]], a first for the program.
